COMPACT_C2 = {
11: {"topic":"Standards bodies","grammar":"Precise institutional register","passage_title":"NIST, ISO, IEEE, IETF: who decides what","passage":"Technical standards are drafted, debated, and ratified by a small constellation of bodies whose authority derives from very different sources. NIST, the National Institute of Standards and Technology, operates under the US Department of Commerce; its publications carry weight in federal procurement and increasingly in international practice. The Federal Information Processing Standards series, FIPS, issues binding requirements for US federal systems. NIST Special Publications, such as SP 800-53, SP 800-207 and SP 800-63, are advisory but widely adopted internationally.\n\nISO, the International Organization for Standardization, operates as a federation of national standards bodies. Standards are developed through consensus across member nations, which produces both the strength of broad legitimacy and the weakness of slow timelines. ISO 27001, the canonical information security management system standard, has been adopted in roughly fifty thousand certifications worldwide. The IEC, the International Electrotechnical Commission, partners with ISO on joint technical committees, including the influential JTC 1 SC 27 on information security.\n\nIEEE, primarily an engineering professional society, develops standards through working groups that participants join voluntarily. Its 802 family — Ethernet, Wi-Fi, and many less famous siblings — underpins the physical and link layers of modern networking.\n\nThe IETF, the Internet Engineering Task Force, is the most distinctive of the major bodies. Membership is informal, decisions are made by 'rough consensus and running code', and the documents — the Request for Comments series — carry technical authority disproportionate to the body's modest formal apparatus.\n\nFor practitioners, navigating standards is a question of identifying which body is authoritative for which problem. NIST for US federal compliance and increasingly for cryptographic primitives. ISO for management systems. IEEE for hardware-adjacent protocols. IETF for internet protocols. Confusion between these — citing IEEE 802.11 in a paper that should reference RFC 8446 — flags the writer as inattentive.","wc":316,"source":"Adapted from public materials of NIST (nist.gov), ISO (iso.org), IEEE-SA, and IETF (ietf.org)."},
12: {"topic":"Conference presentation skills","grammar":"Oratory register","passage_title":"Speaking at security conferences","passage":"Security conferences — Black Hat, DEF CON, USENIX Security, RSA — operate by different conventions, but the speaking skills that work in any of them are recognisable. The opening matters disproportionately. The audience decides within ninety seconds whether to listen actively or to retreat into laptops; speakers who waste those seconds on excessive thanks, agenda reading, or imprecise framing rarely recover.\n\nStructure outranks content for most audiences. A talk built around three clear claims, each developed with a single example, will outperform a talk that crams in seven topics. The 'rule of three' is older than rhetoric and still works. Within each claim, the most effective speakers reveal the conclusion early and then justify it; suspense-driven structures, in which the punchline is reserved for the final slide, work for fewer audiences than presenters assume.\n\nSlides serve speech, not the reverse. Dense slides — those that contain everything the speaker intends to say — produce the irritating dynamic in which the audience reads while the speaker recites. Effective slides are minimal, with single ideas, sparse text, and figures that the speaker walks the audience through orally. The preparation cost is real; the audience reaction is unmistakable.\n\nDemos deserve particular caution. Live demos that fail in front of large audiences are difficult to recover from; recorded demos with live narration produce the same audience experience with substantially less risk. The most experienced speakers prepare for demo failure with a backup recording and a graceful acknowledgement of what is happening. Pretending the demo is working when it is not produces the worst possible outcome.\n\nQuestions deserve preparation in advance. The best speakers anticipate the three or four most likely questions and have prepared answers ready. They also acknowledge questions they cannot fully answer, distinguishing 'I don't know' from 'that is outside the scope of this talk'. Conflating the two reads as evasive; distinguishing them reads as honest, which audiences calibrate against future claims.","wc":341,"source":"Adapted from BlackHat speaker guidelines (public), Carmine Gallo's 'Talk Like TED', and recurring USENIX summit advice."},
13: {"topic":"Writing for top-tier journals","grammar":"Academic writing culture","passage_title":"Publishing in top venues","passage":"Top-tier journal and conference publication is, in security and computer science more broadly, the dominant signal of research seriousness. The metrics — impact factor, h-index, acceptance rate — are imperfect proxies but they are the proxies the field uses, and ignoring them does not change their effect on careers, funding, and citation patterns.\n\nThe writing standards at top venues have shifted noticeably over the past decade. Reproducibility, once aspirational, is now expected; many top venues require artefact submissions and reward reproducible work with badges that appear on the published paper. Author lists have grown; ten-author papers are common in security where they were unusual in 2010. Statistical reporting standards have tightened, with requirements for confidence intervals and effect sizes rather than bare p-values.\n\nThe writing itself rewards a particular discipline. Abstracts are not summaries; they are arguments compressed to two hundred words. Introductions establish what the paper claims and why the claim matters before any technical exposition begins. Methodology sections enable replication, which means specifying not only what was done but the specific tools, parameters, and data sources used. Results are presented before discussion; mixing the two is a common failure that careful editors catch.\n\nA particular convention deserves explicit mention. Negative results — claims that something does not work, or works less well than previously reported — are systematically under-published in computer security. The result is publication bias: reviewers see a stream of positive findings, the practitioner reads of techniques that uniformly succeed, and the literature gives a misleading picture of the state of the field. Recent venue policies that explicitly invite negative results are a corrective. Whether the corrective is sufficient remains contested.\n\nFor researchers building careers, the practical advice is mundane. Read the venue's recent papers. Match their style. Cite carefully. Acknowledge prior work generously. Treat reviews as data rather than as personal feedback. Publish persistently. The compound returns of consistent submission across years dwarf the returns of any single paper, however celebrated.","wc":340,"source":"Adapted from ACM, IEEE, and Usenix author guidelines (public) and Cohen et al. on publication bias in CS."},
14: {"topic":"Grant and proposal writing","grammar":"Bureaucratic English in research funding","passage_title":"Writing grants that get funded","passage":"Research funding, particularly for cybersecurity work, comes from a small set of sources whose conventions vary substantially. Government funders — NSF, NIH, DARPA, the European Research Council, and their counterparts elsewhere — operate with different review processes, different expectations of preliminary data, and different attitudes towards risk. Industry funding, foundation grants, and increasingly open-source sustainability foundations represent additional channels with their own norms.\n\nThe craft of grant writing is partly content and partly form. The content question is whether the proposal addresses a real problem with a credible approach by qualified investigators within a feasible timeline. The form question is whether the proposal communicates these merits clearly enough that overworked reviewers can recognise them in a single reading. Strong proposals, when read by a reviewer who has spent ninety minutes that day on weaker proposals, must still deliver their argument quickly and convincingly.\n\nStructural conventions vary by funder but common elements recur. Aims, sometimes called specific objectives, are the proposal's claims; reviewers evaluate the rest of the proposal against them. Significance establishes why the work matters. Innovation distinguishes the proposed approach from prior work. Approach justifies the methodology choices. Preliminary data, when expected, demonstrates feasibility through evidence the team has already produced. Budget and budget justification translate the proposal into resources. Timelines and milestones translate it into schedule.\n\nA persistent pitfall is mistaking the proposal for a research paper. Proposals are persuasion documents; their structure is rhetorical rather than expository. Burying the central claim in section three because that is where the literature review naturally leads is a mistake that proportionally harms otherwise excellent proposals. Reviewers read in order; the first paragraph, the first page, and the specific aims do disproportionate work.\n\nA second pitfall is over-claiming. Reviewers calibrate against ambition, but over-claiming undermines credibility. Strong proposals identify the most ambitious claim that is genuinely defensible given the team and the resources requested, and stop there.","wc":328,"source":"Adapted from NSF, NIH, DARPA, and ERC public funding documentation, and standard PI training materials."},
15: {"topic":"AI safety and alignment","grammar":"Academic philosophy register","passage_title":"What AI safety actually means","passage":"AI safety is the umbrella term for research and policy concerned with the risks created by increasingly capable artificial intelligence systems. The field has expanded rapidly since 2022 and now spans technical research on alignment, evaluation methodologies, governance frameworks, and emerging international institutions whose authority remains unsettled.\n\nThe distinction between alignment and safety, while not always observed, is informative. Alignment concerns the technical problem of producing AI systems whose behaviour matches the intentions of those who deploy them. Safety is the broader question of whether the deployment of advanced AI systems produces good outcomes for the affected populations, which includes alignment but also encompasses misuse, accident, second-order effects, and the political economy of who benefits.\n\nResearch programmes have crystallised. Reinforcement learning from human feedback has been the dominant training paradigm for instruction-following models since 2022, though its limitations are increasingly documented. Constitutional AI, introduced by Anthropic, replaces some human feedback with model self-critique against a fixed set of principles. Mechanistic interpretability attempts to reverse-engineer trained models to understand what specific weights compute. Each programme addresses a different aspect of the broader problem; none claims to solve it.\n\nGovernance has moved faster than research. The EU AI Act, in force since 2024, imposes obligations proportional to risk; biometric identification systems and critical-infrastructure AI are categorised as high-risk. The US AI Executive Order created the AI Safety Institute. The UK established its own AI Safety Institute earlier. International coordination, through the Bletchley Declaration and successor summits, has produced symbolic alignment among most major economies, though the operational depth of that alignment remains contested.\n\nFor practitioners, the practical implication is that AI components in production systems require operational discipline that the engineering culture of the field has not yet fully internalised. Monitoring for drift, evaluation against red-team challenges, controlled rollout, and staged escalation are increasingly recognised as basic hygiene rather than aspirational. Whether the discipline matures fast enough to keep pace with capability is, at the time of writing, uncertain.","wc":340,"source":"Adapted from Anthropic public papers, NIST AI Risk Management Framework, EU AI Act, UK AI Safety Institute publications."},
16: {"topic":"Deepfakes and disinformation","grammar":"Social-science register","passage_title":"Synthetic media and information integrity","passage":"Synthetic media — images, video, audio, and increasingly text — generated by deep neural networks have reached fidelity levels that defeat casual human detection across most modalities. The term 'deepfake' originally referred to face-swap video produced by adversarial training; it now encompasses the full range of generated media. The asymmetry between generation and detection is, in 2026, decisively in favour of generation.\n\nThe documented harms are diverse. Voice clones have been used in CEO impersonation attacks against finance teams in multiple jurisdictions; the requisite voice samples are now obtainable from a few minutes of public audio. Image and video deepfakes have been deployed in non-consensual intimate imagery, predominantly against women, and in election-period disinformation. Audio deepfakes attempting to influence elections have been documented in Slovakia in 2023 and the United States in 2024.\n\nDefensive techniques operate at multiple layers. Provenance frameworks — most notably the Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity, C2PA — sign content at capture and propagate the signature through editing pipelines, allowing consumers to verify chain of custody. Watermarking embeds detectable signals in generated content; current proposals from major model developers are partial measures whose robustness against adversarial removal remains uneven. Detection classifiers trained to recognise generated content perform well on the data they were trained on and degrade rapidly out of distribution.\n\nThe sociological dimension may be more consequential than the technical one. Even imperfect deepfakes contribute to the 'liar's dividend': the phenomenon in which authentic recordings of misconduct are dismissed as possibly synthetic, regardless of whether they actually are. The harm is not what synthetic media create but what they make plausible.\n\nFor enterprises, the practical defence is procedural. Verification workflows that require multi-channel confirmation for high-stakes requests — never approving wire transfers based on a phone call alone, regardless of the voice — provide defence in depth that no detection technology yet replaces. Public awareness, while imperfect, has improved measurably; the threshold of credulity that attackers must overcome rises every year, even as the capability of their tools rises faster.","wc":350,"source":"Adapted from Stanford Internet Observatory reports, C2PA spec (c2pa.org), academic literature on deepfake detection (e.g., FaceForensics++)."},
17: {"topic":"Biometric security futures","grammar":"Legal-technical fusion","passage_title":"Biometrics: precision, privacy, and policy","passage":"Biometric authentication uses physiological or behavioural characteristics — fingerprints, irises, faces, voices, gaits, keystroke patterns — as proof of identity. The technical maturity is high; commercial systems achieve false-acceptance rates below one in a million on cooperative subjects with quality sensors. The policy questions are correspondingly fraught.\n\nThe technical landscape divides usefully into authentication and identification. Authentication answers the one-to-one question 'is this person who they claim to be', given a presented identity. Identification answers the one-to-many question 'who is this person', searching against a population of templates. The error characteristics differ sharply: false-acceptance rates that are tolerable for authentication become catastrophic at identification scale, where every error is amplified by the size of the gallery searched.\n\nThe regulatory landscape has hardened. The EU AI Act categorises real-time remote biometric identification in publicly accessible spaces as high-risk and subjects it to substantial constraints, with limited exceptions for serious crime. The Illinois Biometric Information Privacy Act, BIPA, imposes private rights of action that have produced billion-dollar settlements against companies that collected biometric data without sufficient consent. Various state-level US laws extend similar protections; the federal landscape remains fragmented.\n\nTemplate protection has become operationally important. Storing raw biometric templates is a privacy risk that increasingly attracts both legal and reputational liability. Cancelable biometrics, fuzzy vaults, fuzzy commitments, and on-device processing through secure enclaves all reduce — though they do not eliminate — the surface for compromise. The recently popularised biometric passkeys built on FIDO2 represent a credible compromise: biometric verification happens on the device, the credential leaving the device is a cryptographic key rather than a biometric, and revocation operates on the key rather than requiring the user to grow new fingerprints.\n\nFor systems engineers, the design principle is straightforward. Biometric data is best treated as keying material that is sensitive but not bearer-secret: matching happens locally, and the network sees only cryptographic artefacts. Architectures that send raw biometric data to the network, regardless of how well-meaning their operational requirements, accumulate compliance and security debt that compounds rapidly.","wc":351,"source":"Adapted from NIST FRVT reports (nist.gov, PD), EU AI Act biometric provisions, BIPA case law (Illinois public legal docs), FIDO Alliance specifications."},
18: {"topic":"Neuromorphic and novel computing","grammar":"Research-frontier register","passage_title":"Beyond von Neumann: neuromorphic, photonic, quantum","passage":"For seventy years, mainstream computing has been organised around the von Neumann architecture: separate memory and processor, with data moving between them on every operation. The bandwidth between memory and processor — the 'von Neumann bottleneck' — has been a recognised limitation since the 1970s and has become acute as compute requirements outpace memory speed gains. Several lines of research aim to circumvent this constraint with architectures fundamentally different from the von Neumann model.\n\nNeuromorphic computing draws inspiration from biological neural networks. Specialised hardware — Intel's Loihi, IBM's TrueNorth, Manchester's SpiNNaker — implements spiking neural networks in silicon, with computation happening at the same physical location as the relevant memory. The energy efficiency is striking: spiking-neural-network implementations of well-suited workloads can consume orders of magnitude less power than conventional GPUs. The applicability remains narrow, however; not all algorithms map to spiking representations efficiently, and the developer ecosystem is correspondingly thin.\n\nIn-memory and near-memory computing represent a less radical departure. Memristive crossbars perform matrix-vector multiplication directly in analogue memory arrays; analogue computation incurs precision limits but extracts performance gains for certain dense linear algebra workloads. Recent commercial systems from companies including Mythic, Rain Neuromorphics, and Lightmatter have shipped silicon, though scale remains modest.\n\nPhotonic computing performs computation with light rather than electrons. Silicon photonics, leveraging existing semiconductor manufacturing infrastructure, has produced credible commercial systems for specific workloads — primarily high-throughput matrix multiplication — at energy efficiencies superior to electronic alternatives. The general-purpose programmability remains limited.\n\nQuantum computing, separately, addresses an entirely different complexity class. Where neuromorphic and photonic systems aim for energy-efficient classical computation, quantum systems attempt to exploit quantum-mechanical phenomena — superposition, entanglement, interference — for problems where classical algorithms scale poorly. Cryptographically relevant quantum computers, capable of running Shor's algorithm against RSA-2048, do not yet exist; the timeline for their arrival is the subject of substantial divergence among informed observers.\n\nFor systems engineers, the lesson of these architectures is that the assumption of indefinite Moore-style scaling on conventional silicon is no longer safe. Designs with multi-decade lifespans need to anticipate architectural diversity that the past five decades did not require.","wc":368,"source":"Adapted from IEEE Spectrum reporting on Loihi, TrueNorth, SpiNNaker; IBM Research blog; Intel public materials; recent NeurIPS and ISCA papers on novel architectures."},
19: {"topic":"Roundtable: emerging tech","grammar":"Polished discussion register","passage_title":"Speaking at high-level roundtables","passage":"Roundtables convene small groups of acknowledged experts, with or without an invited audience, to discuss questions that do not yet have settled answers. The format rewards a particular style of contribution: substantive but not lecturing, opinionated but generous to others, willing to update positions in real time without abandoning core commitments.\n\nThe opening of a roundtable participation deserves disproportionate care. The first contribution from each participant signals their stance, their depth, and — crucially — their willingness to engage with the others. Excessive throat-clearing wastes the floor; immediate disagreement signals confrontation; agreement that adds nothing signals deference. The middle path — building on the previous speaker, adding a specific contribution, and pivoting to a question for others — is what experienced roundtable participants do almost reflexively.\n\nDisagreement requires craft. Disagreeing with a senior figure in a public setting is professionally unavoidable for anyone whose work matters; doing it poorly damages relationships unnecessarily. The convention that has stabilised is to acknowledge the point, identify a specific element of disagreement, and frame the alternative position as a different reading of shared evidence rather than as a refutation of the speaker. 'I would nuance that slightly' is the canonical opening for substantive disagreement at C-suite level; it preserves the working relationship while making the substantive point.\n\nUpdating in real time is the move that distinguishes the most respected participants. When new evidence or arguments are presented during the roundtable, willingness to acknowledge that one's position has shifted — explicitly, in front of the others — signals intellectual honesty in a way that few other moves can. The corresponding failure mode is the participant who clings to a position that has been explicitly undermined, which produces a dynamic that audiences and other panellists immediately recognise.\n\nFor cybersecurity roundtables specifically, the asymmetry between dramatic claims and accurate ones is the recurring tension. Headlines reward the participant who says 'this is an existential threat'; expertise speaks through the participant who says 'with moderate confidence, the impact is contained to the affected segment'. Mature participants accept the headline cost of calibrated language. Audiences over time develop the capacity to distinguish; reputation compounds.","wc":351,"source":"Adapted from BlackHat panel transcripts, OECD AI roundtable proceedings, and Chatham House Rule discussion conventions."},
20: {"topic":"Mock CPE + master capstone","grammar":"C2 grammar recap","passage_title":"Closing the C2 cycle","passage":"This is the final lesson of a programme that has spanned six CEFR levels, one hundred and twenty units of structured study, and what amounts, for a learner who completes it conscientiously, to perhaps eight hundred hours of focused work. The Cambridge C2 Proficiency examination, towards which the final eighteen months have been oriented, tests integrated communicative competence at a level that approaches educated native-speaker performance. By the time you reach the exam, the gap between what the test requires and what you can do should feel small.\n\nThe writing skills the programme has cultivated reach beyond examination performance. The ability to compose a five-thousand-word architecture document that senior colleagues take seriously, to draft a board paper that survives executive committee scrutiny, to write a research paper that secures publication at a top-tier venue — each of these is a downstream consequence of the structural choices that mature C2 writing makes habitually. Cleft sentences, inversion, nominalisation, hedged claims with explicit confidence levels, complex subordination woven through long paragraphs without losing the reader: these are the deliberate tools the programme has placed in your repertoire.\n\nReading evolved similarly. The early levels were vocabulary-limited; mid-levels became syntax-limited as advanced structures multiplied; the C1 level shifted the bottleneck to comprehension as you worked through dense academic prose. At C2, the bottleneck shifts again, this time to inference. C2 prose frequently leaves the most consequential claim implicit, requiring the reader to assemble it from the surrounding text. Recognising what a paper or a strategy document is actually arguing — beyond what it explicitly says — is the C2 skill that separates competent readers from exceptional ones.\n\nSpeaking, finally, has converged with writing in surprising ways. The disciplines of structure, hedging, and metadiscourse that you learned for the page now appear, almost involuntarily, in the conversations you have with international colleagues. They notice. The judgement they make about your professionalism is, at C2, indistinguishable from the judgement they make about a native English speaker of comparable seniority. That convergence is the substance of what C2 actually delivers.\n\nFrom here, what remains is maintenance and use. Languages do not stay still; the only way to keep what you have built is to keep using it. Read three papers a week. Write something substantial every month. Take an opportunity to speak in English you would otherwise have ducked. The compound returns of consistency, here as elsewhere, dwarf the returns of intensity. You have the tools. Use them.","wc":421,"source":"Original. Reflective essay format consistent with Cambridge C2 Proficiency Writing Part 1."}
}

